				\begin{document} $$\begin{array}{@{}rcl@{}} t = a \left(\frac{N}{100} \right)^{L_{C}} \end{array} $$ \end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M6"><mml:mtable class="eqnarray" columnalign="left center right"><mml:mtr><mml:mtd class="eqnarray-1"><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mrow><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>100</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi>L</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>C</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msup></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2020_3743_Article_Equ3.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula></p></list-item></list></p>
    <p>with <italic>N</italic> being the number of miRNAs in a dataset, <italic>L</italic>
<sub><italic>C</italic></sub> the number of miRNAs in a combination-based reference and a regression coefficient. Division by 100 was included to limit the range of values produced after exponentiation. Curves generated in accordance to the above models are shown in Fig. <xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig">2</xref>.</p>
    <p>For the purpose of quantitative comparison, we defined a speed-up gained by CUDA implementation as:
<disp-formula id="Equ4"><label>4</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M7">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
